The paper describes a physician-advisory system for chronic heart failure management that uses answer set programming to code clinical practice guidelines. This involves developing reasoning templates (knowledge patterns) to systematically code the guidelines as ASP rules. The paper also discusses the use of incomplete information in generating treatment recommendations. Based on this, the most likely sub-categories are cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.CL (computation and language), as the paper involves developing a system that uses natural language processing and reasoning to generate recommendations. The use of knowledge patterns also suggests a possible connection to machine learning (cs.LG) and computer engineering (cs.CE). Finally, the paper involves working with large amounts of data and developing a system for managing it, which could be relevant to database systems (cs.DB).
